===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|knyf}}, {{m|enm|knif}}, from late {{inh|en|ang|cnīf}}, from {{der|en|non|knífr}} (compare {{cog|da|-}}/{{cog|sv|-}}/{{cog|no|kniv}}), {{cog|frr|Knif}} from {{der|en|gem-pro|*knībaz}} (compare {{cog|nds|Knief}}, {{cog|lb|Knäip||penknife}}), from {{m|gem-pro|*knīpaną||to pinch}} (compare {{cog|nl|knijpen}}, {{cog|nds|kniepen}}, {{cog|goh|gniffen}}), from {{der|en|ine-pro|*gneybʰ-}} (compare {{cog|lt|gnýbti}}, {{m|lt|žnýbti||to pinch}}, {{m|lt|gnaibis||pinching}}). Replaced {{noncog|enm|sax|t=knife}} from {{noncog|ang|seax|t=knife, dagger}}, and replaced {{noncog|enm|coutel}}, {{m|enm|qwetyll|t=knife}} from {{noncog|fro|coutel|t=knife}}.

The verb ''knife'' is attested since the mid 1800s;<ref>{{R:MWO}}</ref> the variant {{m|en|knive}} is attested since 1733.<!--see entry-->

